\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs28 \cf0 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Paradigms: m. and n. of k\uc0\u257 nta, aham, tvam, sa\u7717 , e\u7779 a\u7717  and ayam; present indicative of as \'91be\'92\
Sanskrit grammarians discussed the cases of the noun in terms of inflexional morphemes modifying the nominal stem. In addition to the vocative (sa\uc0\u7747 buddhi, not regarded as on a par with the other cases), those so far introduced have been the nominative (pratham\u257  \'91first (inflexion)\'92), the accusative (dvit\u299 y\u257  \'91second\'92) and the instrumental (t\u7771 t\u299 y\u257  \'91third\'92). The order of the cases in Sanskrit was principally determined by the wish to group like endings together. The following is a brief sketch (by no means a full account) of the chief uses of the remaining cases.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Dative (caturth\uc0\u299  \'91fourth\'92): \'91to, for\'92\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 Of all the cases the dative has the smallest scope. In Middle Indo-Aryan dialects it was lost, merged into the genitive. Even in Sanskrit itself the tendency of the genitive to usurp the traditional functions of the dative is very noticeable. The dative may be used to denote the indirect object after verbs of giving, telling, etc.:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \uc0\u2342 \u2340 \u2381 \u2340 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2350 \u2351 \u2366 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2348 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2361 \u2381 \u2350 \u2339 \u2375 \u2349 \u2381 \u2351 \u2307 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2381 \u2352 \u2357 \u2367 \u2339 \u2350 \u2381 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b dattam may\uc0\u257  br\u257 hma\u7751 ebhya\u7717  dravi\u7751 am
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i I have given the brahmins wealth.
\f1\i0 \
But in such a sentence the genitive 
\f0\b br\uc0\u257 hma\u7751 \u257 n\u257 m
\f1\b0  may be substituted for the dative.\
However, the dative in Classical Sanskrit does have one function not shared by any other case, that of denoting purpose or result. The best translation in English is often by means of an infinitive:\

\f2\b \uc0\u2354 \u2339 \u2381 \u2337 \u2381 \u2352 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2327 \u2330 \u2381 \u2331 \u2366 \u2350 \u2367 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2344 \u2371 \u2346 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2352 \u2381 \u2358 \u2344 \u2366 \u2351 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b La\uc0\u7751 \u7693 ra\u7747  gacch\u257 mi n\u7771 pasya dar\u347 an\u257 ya
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i I\'92m going to London [for the seeing of:] to see the king.
\f1\i0 \

\f2\b \uc0\u2309 \u2329 \u2381 \u2327 \u2344 \u2366 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2349 \u2329 \u2381 \u2327 \u2366 \u2351 \u2366 \u2352 \u2370 \u2338 \u2366 \u2307 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2348 \u2366 \u2354 \u2366 \u2307 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2325 \u2366 \u2352 \u2307 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b a\uc0\u7749 gan\u257 \u7745  bha\u7749 g\u257 ya \u257 r\u363 \u7693 h\u257 \u7717  b\u257 l\u257 \u7717  pr\u257 k\u257 ra\u7717 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i the children climbed the wall [for the breaking of:] only to break their limbs.
\f1\i0 \
Especially noteworthy is the use of such a dative as a predicate in itself:\

\f2\b \uc0\u2360 \u2352 \u2381 \u2357 \u2350 \u2366 \u2340 \u2367 \u2350 \u2366 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2379 \u2359 \u2366 \u2351 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b sarvam atim\uc0\u257 tram do\u7779 \u257 ya
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i all (that is) excessive [is for a fault:] becomes reprehensible.
\f1\i0 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Ablative (pa\'f1cam\uc0\u299  \'91fifth\'92): \'91from\'92\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 The ablative expresses the relationship \'91from\'92:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \uc0\u2344 \u2327 \u2352 \u2366 \u2340 \u2381 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2325 \u2381 \u2359 \u2375 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2339 \u2367 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2327 \u2330 \u2381 \u2331 \u2340 \u2367 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b nagar\uc0\u257 t k\u7779 etr\u257 \u7751 i gacchati
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i he goes from the city to the fields.
\f1\i0 \
When a causal relationship is implied, translations such as \'91because of\'92 may be used: 
\f2\b \uc0\u2325 \u2381 \u2352 \u2379 \u2343 \u2366 \u2340 \u2381 
\f0  krodh\uc0\u257 t
\f1\b0  \'91from anger\'92, \'91out of anger\'92, \'91because of anger\'92, \'91through anger\'92.\
The ablative of comparison will be mentioned later.\
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Genitive (\uc0\u7779 a\u7779 \u7789 h\u299  \'91sixth\'92): \'91of, \'92s/s\'92\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0 \cf0 The genitive is the case with the widest range of uses. It most often qualifies another substantive and has a possessive sense of some kind:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf0 \uc0\u2344 \u2371 \u2346 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2325 \u2381 \u2352 \u2379 \u2343 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2344 \u2366 \u2357 \u2327 \u2330 \u2381 \u2331 \u2366 \u2350 \u2307 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b n\uc0\u7771 pasya krodha\u7745  na avagacch\u257 ma\u7717 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i we do not understand the king\'92s anger/the anger of the king.
\f1\i0 \
Where the substantive embodies a verbal notion, the relationship may be either subjective or objective, just as the word \'91its\'92 in English is subjective in the phrase \'91its consumption of electricity\'92 and objective in \'91its consumption by the community\'92. 
\f0\b n\uc0\u7771 pasya
\f1\b0  in the preceding example is subjective (the king is angry); in 
\f2\b \uc0\u2344 \u2371 \u2346 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2352 \u2381 \u2358 \u2344 \u2306 
\f0  n\uc0\u7771 pasya dar\u347 anam
\f1\b0 , when this means \'91sight of the king\'92, it is objective (I see the king).\
The use of the genitive as an alternative to the dative after verbs of giving, telling, etc., has been mentioned. Furthermore, it is the genitive and 
\f0\b not
\f1\b0  the dative that should be used in relation to adjectives to express \'91point of view\'92, conveyed in English by \'91to\'92 or \'91for\'92:\

\f2\b \uc0\u2350 \u2367 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2339 \u2366 \u2350 \u2375 \u2357 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2381 \u2352 \u2367 \u2351 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2319 \u2340 \u2340 \u2381 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2352 \u2381 \u2358 \u2344 \u2350 \u2381 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b mitr\uc0\u257 \u7751 \u257 m eva priya\u7745  etat dar\u347 anam
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i to friends, this is a welcome sight.
\f1\i0 \

\f2\b \uc0\u2340 \u2340 \u2381 \u2360 \u2381 \u2341 \u2366 \u2344 \u2375 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2309 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2357 \u2371 \u2358 \u2381 \u2330 \u2354 \u2307 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2375 \u2357 \u2307 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b tat sth\uc0\u257 ne asya V\u7771 \u7779 ala\u7717  deva\u7717 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i Chandragupta\uc0\u7717  then appropriately is His Majesty Chandragupta (just) \'91V\u7771 \u7779 ala\'92 to him.
\f1\i0 \

\f2\b \uc0\u2358 \u2381 \u2352 \u2369 \u2340 \u2350 \u2381 
\f0  \'97 
\f2 \uc0\u2344 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2369 \u2344 \u2307 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2352 \u2381 \u2351 \u2366 \u2346 \u2381 \u2340 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2361 \u2371 \u2342 \u2351 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b \uc0\u347 rutam \'97 na puna\u7717  pary\u257 pta\u7745  h\u7771 dayasya
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i (I) have heard, yet (it is) not sufficient for (my) heart.
\f1\i0 \
Similarly, past participles formed from roots meaning \'91to know\'92, \'91to desire\'92 or \'91to honour\'92, such as 
\f2\b \uc0\u2357 \u2367 \u2342 \u2367 \u2340 
\f0  vidita
\f1\b0  \'91known\'92, take a genitive (instead of an instrumental of the agent) when used adjectivally:\

\f2\b \uc0\u2309 \u2346 \u2367 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2357 \u2367 \u2342 \u2367 \u2340 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2319 \u2340 \u2340 \u2381 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2375 \u2357 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b api viditam etat devasya
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i is this known to Your Majesty?
\f1\i0 \
But:\

\f2\b \uc0\u2309 \u2346 \u2367 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2357 \u2367 \u2342 \u2367 \u2340 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2375 \u2357 \u2375 \u2344 \u2366 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2340 \u2375 \u2359 \u2366 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2309 \u2349 \u2367 \u2346 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2351 \u2307 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b api viditam devena te\uc0\u7779 \u257 \u7745  abhipr\u257 ya\u7717 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i did Your Majesty (get to) know their intentions?
\f1\i0 \
The possessive adjective 
\f2\b \uc0\u2350 \u2342 \u2368 \u2351 
\f0  mad\uc0\u299 ya
\f1\b0  \'91my, mine\'92 was given in the previous chapter. There are various others\'97e.g. 
\f2\b \uc0\u2350 \u2366 \u2350 \u2325 
\f0  m\uc0\u257 maka
\f1\b0  (same meaning), 
\f2\b \uc0\u2351 \u2369 \u2359 \u2381 \u2350 \u2342 \u2368 \u2351 
\f0  yu\uc0\u7779 mad\u299 ya
\f1\b0  \'91belonging to (all of) you\'92, etc. More commonly, however, the genitive of the appropriate pronoun is used instead of the possessive adjective:\

\f2\b \uc0\u2350 \u2350 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2327 \u2371 \u2361 \u2350 \u2381 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b mama g\uc0\u7771 ham
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i [the house of me:] my house.
\f1\i0 \

\f2\b \uc0\u2350 \u2350 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2325 \u2381 \u2359 \u2375 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2339 \u2367 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b mama k\uc0\u7779 etr\u257 \u7751 i
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i my fields.
\f1\i0 \

\f2\b \uc0\u2340 \u2357 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2369 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2307 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b tava putr\uc0\u257 \u7717 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i your sons
\f1\i0  (addressing one person).\

\f2\b \uc0\u2351 \u2369 \u2359 \u2381 \u2350 \u2366 \u2325 \u2306 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2369 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2307 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b yu\uc0\u7779 m\u257 ka\u7745  putr\u257 \u7717 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i your sons
\f1\i0  (addressing several persons).\

\f2\b \uc0\u2325 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2369 \u2359 \u2381 \u2346 \u2366 \u2339 \u2367 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b kasya pu\uc0\u7779 p\u257 \u7751 i
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i whose flowers?
\f1\i0 \

\f2\b \uc0\u2340 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2361 \u2360 \u2381 \u2340 \u2380 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b tasya hastau
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i his hands.
\f1\i0 \
The unemphatic forms of the first and second person pronouns (
\f2\b \uc0\u2350 \u2375 
\f0  me, 
\f2 \uc0\u2344 \u2380 
\f0  nau
\f1\b0 , etc.) may also be used. Like the ordinary forms, they may either precede or follow their substantive, but as enclitics they may not stand first in the sentence:\

\f2\b \uc0\u2311 \u2350 \u2375 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2344 \u2379 
\f0  
\f2 \uc0\u2327 \u2371 \u2361 \u2366 \u2307 \u2404 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f0\b ime no g\uc0\u7771 h\u257 \u7717 
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f3\i here is our house
\f1\i0  (the plural of 
\f0\b g\uc0\u7771 ha
\f1\b0  often has a singular sense).\
Generally speaking, neither possessive adjectives nor the genitives of pronouns may be used to refer to the subject or \'91logical subject\'92 of a sentence. If necessary, the reflexive adjective 
\f2\b \uc0\u2360 \u2381 \u2357 
\f0  sva
\f1\b0  \'91my own, your own, his own, their own, etc.\'92 or the genitive singular of the reflexive word 
\f4 \uc0\u2310 \u2340 \u2381 \u2350 \u2344 \u2381 
\f1  \uc0\u257 tman 'self' may be employed, but it is usually omitted unless exceptional emphasis is intended. [sva is often compounded with its substantive, while as a separate word \u257 tmanah\u803  is more normal.]\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f4 \cf0 \uc0\u2346 \u2369 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2344 \u2381 \u2352 \u2325 \u2381 \u2359 \u2340 \u2367 
\f1  putr\uc0\u257 n rak\u7779 ati\u8232 he protects his sons\

\f4 \uc0\u2340 \u2360 \u2381 \u2351 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2346 \u2369 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2344 \u2381 \u2352 \u2325 \u2381 \u2359 \u2340 \u2367 
\f1  tasya putr\uc0\u257 n rak\u7779 ati\u8232 he protects his [i.e. the other's] sons\

\f4 \uc0\u2360 \u2381 \u2357 \u2366 \u2344 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2319 \u2357 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2346 \u2369 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2344 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2352 \u2325 \u2381 \u2359 \u2360 \u2367 
\f1  sv\uc0\u257 n eva putr\u257 n rak\u7779 asi\u8232 you protect your own sons\
Because the omission of the reflexive possessive is standard, it is from now on not normally indicated in the exercises by any bracketing of the English word: 'he protects his sons', not 'he protects (his) sons'.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf0 Locative
\f1\b0  (saptam\uc0\u299  'seventh'): 'at, in, on, among; into, onto'\
The locative expresses such notions as station or circumstance:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f4 \cf0 \uc0\u2330 \u2352 \u2340 \u2367 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2357 \u2344 \u2375 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2325 \u2367 \u2350 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2330 \u2367 \u2340 \u2381 
\f1  carati vane kim\uc0\u803  cit\u8232 something is moving in the forest\

\f4 \uc0\u2347 \u2354 \u2325 \u2374 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2348 \u2366 \u2354 \u2366 \u2307 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2313 \u2346 \u2357 \u2367 \u2359 \u2381 \u2335 \u2366 \u2307 
\f1  phalake b\uc0\u257 l\u257 h\u803  upavi\u7779 \u7789 \u257 h\u803 \u8232 the children are seated on the table\

\f4 \uc0\u2350 \u2367 \u2340 \u2381 \u2352 \u2366 \u2339 \u2366 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2342 \u2352 \u2381 \u2358 \u2344 \u2374 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2344 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2325 \u2367 \u2350 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2330 \u2367 \u2340 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2357 \u2342 \u2340 \u2367 
\f1  mitr\uc0\u257 n\u257 m dar\u347 ane na kim\u803  cit vadati\u8232 [at the sight of:] on seeing his friends he says nothing\
It also expresses the end result of motion:\

\f4 \uc0\u2332 \u2354 \u2375 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2348 \u2366 \u2354 \u2350 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2325 \u2381 \u2359 \u2367 \u2346 \u2340 \u2367 
\f1  jale b\uc0\u257 lam\u803  k\u7779 ipati\u8232 he throws the child into the water\
It can bear the sense 'in the matter of':\

\f4 \uc0\u2309 \u2346 \u2366 \u2346 \u2379 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2365 \u2361 \u2306 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2346 \u2352 \u2381 \u2357 \u2340 \u2375 \u2358 \u2381 \u2357 \u2352 \u2374 
\f1  ap\uc0\u257 pah\u803  aham\u803  Parvate\u347 vare\u8232 [in the matter of:] I am guiltless towards Parvate\u347 vara\
In particular, it is used to denote the object of feelings (English 'towards', 'for'):\

\f4 \uc0\u2309 \u2357 \u2327 \u2330 \u2381 \u2331 \u2366 \u2350 \u2367 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2340 \u2375 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2340 \u2360 \u2381 \u2350 \u2367 \u2344 \u2381 \u2360 \u2380 \u2361 \u2366 \u2352 \u2381 \u2342 \u2350 \u2381 
\f1  avagacch\uc0\u257 mi te tasmin sauh\u257 rdam\u8232 I understand your fondness for him\
It thus occurs after a verb such as 
\f4 \uc0\u2360 \u2381 \u2344 \u2367 \u2361 \u2381 
\f1  snih 'feel affection (for)':\

\f4 \uc0\u2325 \u2367 \u2350 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2344 \u2369 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2326 \u2354 \u2369 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2348 \u2366 \u2354 \u2374 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2309 \u2360 \u2381 \u2350 \u2367 \u2344 \u2381 
\f1  
\f4 \uc0\u2324 \u2340 \u2381 \u2360 \u2374 
\f1  
