\f0\b ata\uc0\u7717 : atah\u803 
\f1\b0 ), the other 
\f0\b i
\f1\b0  (cf. 
\f0\b iha
\f1\b0  and 
\f0\b itah\uc0\u803 : itah\u803 
\f1\b0 ).\
Two pronouns are conventionally translated by the English 
\f3\i 'that'
\f1\i0 : 
\f2\b \uc0\u2360 \u2307 
\f0  sa\uc0\u7717 
\f1\b0  and 
\f2\b \uc0\u2309 \u2360 \u2380 
\f0  asau
\f1\b0  (Chapter 13); and two by the English 
\f3\i 'this':
\f1\i0  
\f2\b \uc0\u2309 \u2351 \u2350 \u2381 
\f0  ayam
\f1\b0  and 
\f2\b \uc0\u2319 \u2359 \u2307 
\f0  e\uc0\u7779 a\u7717 
\f1\b0 . Traditionally, the distinctions are that 
\f0\b sa\uc0\u7717 
\f1\b0  is used of what is not present to the speaker, 
\f0\b asau
\f1\b0  of what is remote from him (though possibly visible), 
\f0\b ayam
\f1\b0  of what is present, and 
\f0\b e\uc0\u7779 a\u7717 
\f1\b0  of what is near at hand.\
Thus 
\f0\b asau
\f1\b0  is the 'stronger' of the two which mean 
\f3\i 'that'
\f1\i0 , 
\f0\b e\uc0\u7779 a\u7717 
\f1\b0  the 'stronger' of the two which mean 
\f3\i 'this'
\f1\i0 .
\f0\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \
