\f0\b The absolutive
\f1\b0 \
Of an ancient verbal action noun in 
\f0\b -tu
\f1\b0  (cf. the Latin supine) two cases survive in Classical Sanskrit: the accusative, supplying the Sanskrit infinitive (
\f2\b \uc0\u2344 \u2375 \u2340 \u2369 \u2350 \u2381 
\f0  netum \'91to lead\'92,
\f1\b0  with strengthening of the root), and the instrumental, supplying the absolutive (or \'91gerund\'92, or \'91indeclinable participle\'92)\'97
\f2\b \uc0\u2344 \u2368 \u2340 \u2381 \u2357 \u2366 
\f0  n\uc0\u299 tv\u257  \'91after leading, by leading\'92,
\f1\b0  with weak grade of the root.\
The absolutive in 
\f0\b -tv\uc0\u257 
\f1\b0  is not difficult to form. With very few exceptions it may be obtained by substituting 
\f0\b tv\uc0\u257 
\f1\b0  for the 
\f0\b -ta
\f1\b0  or 
\f0\b -na
\f1\b0  of the past participle (with internal sandhi as appropriate). So 
\f2\b \uc0\u2313 \u2325 \u2381 \u2340 \u2381 \u2357 \u2366 
\f0  uktv\uc0\u257  \'91after saying\'92, 
\f2 \uc0\u2342 \u2371 \u2359 \u2381 \u2335 \u2381 \u2357 \u2366 
\f0  dr\uc0\u803 s\u803 tv\u257  \'91after seeing\'92, 
\f2 \uc0\u2354 \u2348 \u2381 \u2343 \u2381 \u2357 \u2366 
\f0  labdhv\uc0\u257  \'91after taking\'92, 
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2340 \u2367 \u2340 \u2381 \u2357 \u2366 
\f0  patitv\uc0\u257  \'91after falling\'92, 
\f2 \uc0\u2340 \u2368 \u2352 \u2381 \u2340 \u2381 \u2357 \u2366 
\f0  t\uc0\u299 rtv\u257  \'91after crossing\'92.
\f1\b0 \
The absolutive in 
\f0\b -tv\uc0\u257 
\f1\b0  may 
\f0\b not
\f1\b0  be used when a verb is compounded with a prefix or prefixes. In such a case the suffix 
\f0\b -ya
\f1\b0  (probably itself the instrumental of an old action noun in 
\f0\b -i
\f1\b0 ) is added to the verb, which usually appears in its weaker form. In internal sandhi, fortunately, 
\f0\b y
\f1\b0  is without effect on the preceding sound. Roots ending in a short vowel add 
\f0\b -tya
\f1\b0  instead of 
\f0\b -ya
\f1\b0 , and those roots ending in 
\f0\b -an/-am
\f1\b0  which shorten to 
\f0\b -a
\f1\b0  in the past participle may 
\f0\b optionally
\f1\b0  do so (again shortening to 
\f0\b -a
\f1\b0 ). So\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b \uc0\u2360 \u2306 \u2342 \u2371 \u2358 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  samdr\uc0\u803 \u347 ya \'91after seeing\'92, 
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2381 \u2352 \u2340 \u2381 \u2351 \u2369 \u2340 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  pratyutya \'91after replying\'92, 
\f2 \uc0\u2357 \u2367 \u2332 \u2367 \u2340 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  vijitya \'91after conquering\'92, 
\f2 \uc0\u2310 \u2327 \u2350 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  \uc0\u97 \u772 gamya
\f1\b0  or 
\f2\b \uc0\u2310 \u2327 \u2340 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  \uc0\u97 \u772 gatya \'91after coming\'92.
\f1\b0 \
(A minor exception to both the above formations is provided by derivative verbs in 
\f0\b -ayati.
\f1\b0  They form their past participle in 
\f0\b -ita
\f1\b0  but their simple absolutive in 
\f0\b -ayitv\uc0\u257 .
\f1\b0  In the compounded absolutive, they substitute 
\f0\b -ya
\f1\b0  for 
\f0\b -ayati
\f1\b0  in general but 
\f0\b -ayya
\f1\b0  if the vowel of the stem is unstrengthened. So\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b \uc0\u2327 \u2350 \u2351 \u2367 \u2340 \u2381 \u2357 \u2366 
\f0  gamayitv\uc0\u257  \'91after causing to go\'92, 
\f2 \uc0\u2310 \u2327 \u2350 \u2351 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  \uc0\u97 \u772 gamayya \'91after causing to come\'92, 
\f2 \uc0\u2346 \u2381 \u2352 \u2357 \u2375 \u2358 \u2381 \u2351 
\f0  prave\uc0\u347 ya \'91after causing to enter\'92.
\f1\b0  See pp. 85\'967.)\
The sense of the absolutive is generally that of action preceding the action of the main verb. Its closest equivalent is often therefore in primer English the perfect participle (
\f3\i \'91having led\'92
\f1\i0 ) and in ordinary English the present participle (
\f3\i \'91leading\'92
\f1\i0 ).\

