\f0\b \cf0 Khalu
\f1\b0 \uc0\u8232 
\f4 \uc0\u2326 \u2354 \u2369 
\f1  
\f3\i khalu
\f1\i0 , like 
\f4 \uc0\u2319 \u2357 
\f1  
\f3\i eva
\f1\i0 , is an enclitic particle of emphasis. But whereas 
\f3\i eva
\f1\i0  is an affirmative particle stressing what is new, 
\f3\i khalu
\f1\i0  is a confirmatory particle tending to stress what is already implicitly known. In consequence, whereas 
\f3\i eva
\f1\i0  often marks out a predicate, 
\f3\i khalu
\f1\i0  may equally well qualify the subject (or perhaps spread its emphasis more evenly over the whole statement). The subject is then usually placed first in the sentence. For convenience, 
\f3\i khalu
\f1\i0  is represented in the exercises by 'indeed'.
